{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Missionary Day |type = Official holiday |image =The missionary ship "Duff" arriving (ca. 1797) at Otaheite, lithograph by Kronheim & Co.jpg |imagesize = |caption = The missionary ship ''Duff'' arriving in Tahiti, 1797 |official_name = |nickname = |observedby = French Polynesia |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = To mark the arrival of the London Missionary Society (LMS) missionaries in 1797 |begins = |ends = |date = 5 March |scheduling = Same day each year |duration = 1 day |frequency = Annual |week_ordinal = <!-- "first", "second", "last", etc. --> |weekday = <!-- "Sunday", "Monday", "Friday", etc. --> |month = <!-- "January", "February", "December", etc. --> <!-- Use next four if the date changes in an unusual pattern each year --> |date2016 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2017 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2018 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2019 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |celebrations = Cultural shows, public concerts and other events of cultural significance |observances = Re-enactment of first landing |relatedto = }}
'''Missionary Day''' ({{lang-fr|Arrivée de l'Évangile}})<ref name="KennedyStudies2001">{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=David M.|author2=Center for International Studies|title=Africa, Asia, and Oceania: Culturegrams 2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N1J5OfM0W_AC|year=2001|publisher=CultureGrams|location=Orem, UT|isbn=978-0-89434-421-3|pages=100|oclc=48029327}}</ref> is an official holiday in [[French Polynesia]], an overseas collectivity of [[France]]. It is celebrated annually on 5 March, to mark the arrival of the [[London Missionary Society]] (LMS) missionaries in 1797 when their ship ''[[Duff (1794 ship)|Duff]]'' landed at [[Matavai Bay]].<ref name="AGW" /> It is a non-working holiday.<ref name="KennedyStudies2001" />
== History == On 5 March 1797, British Protestant missionaries from the [[London Missionary Society]] landed at [[Matavai Bay]], in [[Mahina, French Polynesia|Mahina]], Tahiti, on board ''[[Duff (1794 ship)|Duff]]''. Despite early setbacks in the mission, the LMS missionaries were able to convert the reigning king [[Pōmare II]], who sought to use the new religion to consolidate his own power over the other chiefs of the island. The king was formally baptized on 16 May 1819, and the rest of the [[kingdom of Tahiti]] followed. Protestantism gained a strong following with the [[Tahitian people]] through the patronage of the [[Pōmare Dynasty]] and other chiefly families of the neighboring [[Society Islands]]. Even when Tahiti became a French protectorate in 1843 and was annexed in 1880, Protestantism remained the dominant religion among the natives.<ref name="Garrett1982">{{cite book|last=Garrett|first=John|chapter=|title=To Live Among the Stars: Christian Origins in Oceania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7HYexAnWCoC|year=1982|publisher=Institute of Pacific Studies, [[University of the South Pacific]]|location=Suva, Fiji|isbn=978-2-8254-0692-2|oclc=17485209|pages=14-31, 253–260}}</ref>
The holiday was established on 1 February 1978.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chronologie|work=Histoire de l'Assemblée de la Polynésie française|url=http://histoire.assemblee.pf/articles.php?id=568|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>
== Celebrations == The parishes of the [[Maohi Protestant Church]] hold organized celebrations and worship services. The holiday is also marked by cultural shows, public concerts and other events of cultural significance. Traditionally, the arrival of the first missionaries in 1797 is re-enacted at the Willy Bambridge Stadium complex in [[Papeete]], [[Tahiti]], as well as on [[Afareaitu]], [[Moorea]].<ref name="AGW">{{cite web|title=French Polynesia Observes Missionary Day|website=AGlobalWorld.com|url=http://aglobalworld.com/holidays-around-the-world/french-polynesia-missionary-day/|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Saura|first=Bruno|title=Histoire et mémoire des temps coloniaux en Polynésie française|location=Papeete|publisher=Au vent des îles|year=2015|isbn=978-2-36734-081-4|url=http://www.auventdesiles.pf/catalogue/collections/culture-oceanienne/histoire-et-memoire-des-temps-coloniaux-en-polynesie-francaise/|page=118}}</ref>
The commune of [[Arue, French Polynesia|Arue]] commemorates the festival by laying wreaths at the graves of the first Christian king Pōmare II and [[Henry Nott]], a member of the first company of missionaries who translated the Bible into the [[Tahitian language]].<ref>{{cite news|title=L'arrivée de l'Évangile célébrée|work=Tahiti Infos|date=5 March 2016|url=http://www.tahiti-infos.com/L-arrivee-de-l-Evangile-celebree_a145512.html|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>
