'''Provection''' (from Latin: ''provectio'' "advancement") is a linguistic term referring to the carrying over of the final [[consonant]] of a word to the following word. Examples in English include ''newt'' from earlier ''an ewte'' and ''nickname'' from earlier ''an eke name''. It is also observed in [[Celtic languages]], both [[Scottish Gaelic]], noted in ''The Gaelic of Arran'' by [[Nils Holmer|Nils Magnus Holmer]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zmZiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Provection%22&dq=%22Provection%22&hl=en&ei=9CrbTs6VNcWMmQWi_7TrBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ |title=The Gaelic of Arran - Nils Magnus Holmer - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref> and extensively in [[Breton language|Breton]] grammar.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PzKa-iSAWggC&pg=PA575&dq=%22Provection%22&hl=en&ei=9CrbTs6VNcWMmQWi_7TrBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Provection%22&f=false |title=Breton Orthographies and Dialects: The Twentieth-Century Orthography War in ... - Iwan Wmffre - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref>

