{{more citations needed|date=December 2011}} The '''Ultraverse''' was a [[comic book]] [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]] published by the [[American comic book|American]] company [[Malibu Comics]] which is owned by [[Marvel Comics]]. The Ultraverse was a [[shared universe]] in which a variety of characters—known within the comics as "[[Ultras (comics)|Ultras]]"—acquired super-human abilities.
==History== The Ultraverse line was launched by [[Malibu Comics]] during the "comics boom" of the early 1990s. Ultraverse emphasized tight [[Continuity (fiction)|continuity]] between the various series in their line; Malibu made extensive use of [[fictional crossover|crossover]]s, in which a story that began in one series would be continued in the next-shipping issue of another series. Various promotions for special editions or limited-print stories also encouraged readers to sample issues of the entire line. The Ultraverse line came to dominate Malibu's catalog. Several characters from the series [[Ultraforce]] were featured in a short-lived animated series by the same name.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
As American comics sales declined in the mid-1990s, Malibu canceled lower-selling series. The company was purchased by [[Marvel Comics]] in 1994. Reportedly Marvel made the purchase to acquire Malibu's then-groundbreaking in-house coloring studio. In reality, Marvel purchased the line to prevent DC Comics from buying Malibu, in order to increase DC's market share.<ref>Cronin, Brian (December 16, 2016). [http://www.cbr.com/comic-legends-why-did-marvel-really-buy-the-ultraverse/ "Comic Legends: Why Did Marvel REALLY Buy the Ultraverse?"]. [[CBR.com]].</ref>
Marvel canceled the entire Ultraverse line, but (during the controversial ''Black September'' event) re-launched a handful of the more popular titles as well as a number of [[Intercompany crossover|crossovers]] with Marvel characters. The initial move was foreseen with popular franchises and characters from the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] guest-starring in their books. The "volume 2" series each started with "#[[infinity|∞]]" (infinity) issues and were canceled a short time later. Within the [[Multiverse (Marvel Comics)|Marvel Comics multiverse]], the Malibu Universe is designated as '''Earth-93060'''.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
==Black September== {{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}} When Malibu was bought out by [[Marvel Comics]], the entire Ultraverse line was cancelled and restarted. Only a few of the more popular series were [[Reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] and relaunched, with some being radically altered. The history and continuity of the Ultraverse was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] in numerous ways, and a number of characters simply ceased to exist (or in the new continuity, to have ever existed). This now-modified Ultraverse lasted less than a year and a half before being cancelled once again.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
The event connects issues that were part of the countdown to Black September — ''[[Ultraforce (comics)|Ultraforce]]'' #8-10, ''Ultraforce/Avengers Prelude'', ''[[Avengers/Ultraforce]]'', ''Ultraforce/Avengers'' — after which all the surviving Ultraverse titles restarted with a special "∞"-numbered issue.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
==Revival== In June 2005, when asked by [[Newsarama]] whether Marvel had any plans to revive the Ultraverse, Marvel editor-in-chief [[Joe Quesada]] replied:
{{quote|Let's just say that I wanted to bring these characters back in a very big way, but the way that the deal was initially structured, it's next to impossible to go back and publish these books.
There are rumors out there that it has to do with a certain percentage of sales that has to be doled out to the creative teams. While this is a logistical nightmare because of the way the initial deal was structured, it's not the reason why we have chosen not to go near these characters, there is a bigger one, but I really don't feel like it's my place to make that dirty laundry public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/JoeFridays/JoeFridays9.html |title=Joe Fridays - Week 9|date=May 2005 |work=[[Newsarama]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060323215618/http://www.newsarama.com/JoeFridays/JoeFridays9.html |archivedate=March 23, 2006}}</ref>}}
Senior Vice President of Publishing [[Tom Brevoort]] has stated in the past that the reason Marvel cannot discuss the Ultraverse properties is because of [[non disclosure agreements]] in place with certain parties, which has been speculated to pertain to [[Scott Mitchell Rosenberg]]'s contractual position as "ongoing producer deal for all Malibu Comics properties".<ref>De Blieck, Augie Jr. (December 17, 2013). [https://www.cbr.com/miracleman-malibus-coloring-department-more/ "Miracleman, Malibu's Coloring Department & More!"] CBR.com.</ref>
